Israel Stocks: BluePhoenix, Clal, Discount, Gilat, ICL, IDB

-- B y   R o n i t   G o o d m a n
-- 
2011-03-28T15:25:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-28/israel-stocks-clal-d-medical-discount-investment-idb.html
Israel’s TA-25 Index gained 0.4
percent to 1,311.51 at the 4:30 p.m. close in  Tel Aviv , bringing
the loss this quarter to 1.1 percent. Investors traded about
1.41 billion shekels ($399 million) in shares and convertible
securities.  The following stocks rose or fell today. Symbols are in
parentheses.  BluePhoenix Solutions Ltd. (BPHX)   advanced to the
highest level in three weeks, increasing 1.4 percent to 6.563
shekels. The company that upgrades software packages was awarded
an $840,000 contract from a European financial company.  Clal Insurance Enterprise Holdings Ltd. (CLIS)   climbed
to the highest in five weeks, gaining 4.2 percent to 98.99
shekels. Fourth-quarter net income soared to 168 million shekels
from 22 million shekels a year earlier. The insurance holding
company set a total dividend of 150 million shekels.  Separately, Globes reported that IDB Holding Corp. (IDBH
IT) is in talks to sell its stake in Clal to a European
insurance company. A representative for IDB told Bloomberg today
a number of parties have shown interest in Clal. IDB decreased
1.2 percent to 118.80 shekels.  D. Medical Industries Ltd. (DMED IT) jumped the most since
July 5, soaring 13 percent to 12.80 shekels. The developer of
drug-delivery devices said a subcontractor began mass production
of its Spring Universal Infusion Sets in  China .  Discount Investment Corp. (DISI)   rose to the highest
since Feb. 22, adding 2.2 percent to 71.15 shekels. Billionaire
Nochi Dankner’s holding company reported a fourth-quarter loss
that narrowed to 175 million shekels from 245 million shekels a
year earlier. The company set a total dividend of 180 million
shekels, payable April 28.  Gilat Satellite Networks Ltd. (GILT)   increased to the
highest since March 13, rising 2.4 percent to 17.94 shekels. The
Peruvian unit of the developer of satellite-network technology
won a five-year, $14.5 million contract from Peru’s Agency for
Promotion of Private Investment to provide Internet access and
technology services throughout the country’s rural regions.  Israel Chemicals Ltd. (ICL)   climbed to the highest in a
month, advancing 1.7 percent to 60 shekels. The company that
extracts minerals from the  Dead Sea  to make fertilizer reported
a 21 percent increase in fourth-quarter profit to $245.4 million
as potash sales volumes and prices increased.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ronit Goodman in Tel Aviv at 
